    <h1>Managing contacts</h1><div id="preamble">
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="admonitionblock important">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-important" title="Important"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Note about the "Managing contacts" page of the manual</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This page of the manual describes all settings that are available in the <strong>CRM » Contacts</strong> menu in the Terra back end using the centralised login. The <a href="/en/crm/managing-customer-data">Managing customer data</a> page of the manual that describes the settings in the <strong>CRM » Edit customers</strong> and <strong>System »Customers</strong> menus will be simultaneously available. Once the new <strong>CRM » Contacts</strong> menu has completely replaced the old <strong>CRM » Edit customers</strong> menu, the <strong>CRM » Edit customers</strong> menu as well as the <strong>Managing customer data</strong> page of the manual will be removed.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Go to <strong>CRM » Contacts</strong> to create and edit data records for your contacts and manage all relevant information there such as addresses, orders, scheduled orders, tickets, notes, account balance, bank data and documents.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock tip">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-tip" title="Tip"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Notes about detail view, context menu, card view and table view</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you click on a contact in order to display or edit it, the detail view of the contact will open. Via the context menu in the left section of the contact, you can access views such as <strong>Addresses</strong> or <strong>New address</strong>.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>By clicking on <strong>Addresses</strong> for example, all addresses that are saved for the contact will be initially displayed as cards. By clicking on <strong>Switch to table view</strong>, the addresses will be displayed in a table. From this view, you can switch back by clicking on <strong>Switch to card view</strong>. Your plentymarkets system will recognise which of the two views you selected. When opening the context menu <strong>Addresses</strong> the next time, the view that was selected last will be displayed.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>When more than one view of the contact is open, a triangle will appear in the view above. Click on the triangle to quickly and easily switch between the open views. Click on the cross to close the contact and remove it from the list.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You can get back to the overview of contacts found via the <strong>Overview</strong> view. From this view, you can open as many further contacts as you like. When more than one contact is open, a triangle will appear in the view of the contact that is currently open. Click on the triangle to quickly and easily access contacts that have been opened at least once. Click on the cross to close the contact and remove it from the list.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="50">1. Setting up the visibility for variable user</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In order that the <strong>CRM » Contacts</strong> menu is visible for users with the user class <strong>Variable</strong>, the menu must be activated in the user account. For users with the user class <strong>Admin</strong>, the <strong>CRM » Contacts</strong> menu is activated by default.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Setting up the visibility for variable user:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>System » Settings » User » Accounts</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Open the user with the user class <strong>Variable</strong> for whom you would like to make activate the visibility of the menu.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on the <strong>Right</strong> tab.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on the <strong>Menu</strong> tab.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Expand the <strong>Customer</strong> area.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Activate the <strong>Contacts</strong> option.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Save</strong> the setting.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="90">2. Managing contacts</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In the following sub-chapters, you will learn how to create new contacts, search for existing contacts using the filter settings as well as edit and delete existing contacts.</p>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="100">2.1. Creating a contact</h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Proceed as described below to create a new contact. Add contact options such as email addresses, telephone numbers and, if required, the VAT number. You can also create a new contact, for example, while taking an order over the phone or while filling out a written order. It is also possible to save the contact details of interested parties here. When creating a contact, the system will automatically assign an ID. This ID cannot be changed.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Creating a contact:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>CRM » Contacts</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Create new contact</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Carry out the settings as desired in the <strong>New contact</strong> section. Pay attention to the information given in <a href="#table-create-contact">Table 1</a>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>In the <strong>Contact options</strong> section, select the type and sub-type from the drop-down menu and enter the value. Pay attention to the information given in <a href="#table-create-contact">Table 1</a>.<br>
→ Click on <strong>Add contact option</strong> to add further contact options.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Save</strong> the settings.<br>
→ The contact will be added.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
